# 🧠 What is Caching?

Caching is a technique where frequently used data is stored in a **fast storage layer (usually RAM)** so it can be accessed quickly later.
Instead of asking the database every time, the system first checks cache and returns data much faster.

📌 Example:
Popular product details stored in Redis cache → page loads in milliseconds instead of querying DB each time.

# 🎯 Why Use Caching?

Caching reduces response time, lowers database load, and helps systems handle more users.
It is one of the easiest ways to improve performance without changing business logic.

📌 Example:
1000 users request same homepage → serve from cache instead of hitting DB 1000 times.

# 🔁 Basic Flow of Cache

Application first checks cache for data.
If found, return immediately. If not found, fetch from DB and store in cache.

📌 Example:
Request product 101 → cache miss → DB fetch → save in cache → next request becomes cache hit.

# 📦 Types of Caching

# 🧠 1. In-Memory Cache

Stores data in RAM for very fast access.
Used for sessions, frequently accessed objects, counters, and hot data.

📌 Example:
Redis stores logged-in user session.

# 🌐 2. Distributed Cache

Cache spread across multiple servers so many applications can use it together.
Useful in large systems where one cache server is not enough.

📌 Example:
Redis Cluster used by multiple app servers.

# 💻 3. Client-Side Cache

Data stored on user device or browser.
Used for static files and repeated UI assets.

📌 Example:
Browser caches CSS, JS, images.

# 🗄️ 4. Database Cache

Stores query results or expensive DB responses.
Reduces repeated queries to database.

📌 Example:
Top 10 products query cached for 5 minutes.

# 🌍 5. CDN Cache

Static content stored in global edge servers close to users.
Reduces latency for users in different countries.

📌 Example:
Image requested in India served from nearby CDN node.

# 🛠️ Caching Strategies

# 📖 1. Read-Through Cache

Application asks cache first. If data missing, cache fetches from DB automatically.
Simple for reads and keeps logic centralized.

📌 Example:
Get user profile → cache loads from DB on miss.

# ✍️ 2. Write-Through Cache

Write goes to cache and DB together.
Improves consistency but writes become slower.

📌 Example:
Update profile name → cache + DB both updated instantly.

# 🚀 3. Write-Back Cache

Write goes to cache first, DB updated later asynchronously.
Very fast writes but risk of data loss if cache crashes before sync.

📌 Example:
Gaming score updates buffered in cache then flushed later.

# 💤 4. Cache-Aside (Most Common)

Application manages cache manually.
Read from cache, on miss read DB and populate cache.

📌 Example:
E-commerce product details loaded lazily into Redis.

# 🗑️ Cache Eviction Policies

# ⏱️ 1. LRU (Least Recently Used)

Removes item not used recently.
Assumes recently used data is more valuable.

📌 Example:
Old product page removed when cache full.

# 🔢 2. LFU (Least Frequently Used)

Removes item used least number of times.
Useful when popularity matters.

📌 Example:
Rarely opened article removed first.

# 📦 3. FIFO (First In First Out)

Oldest inserted item removed first.
Simple but less intelligent.

📌 Example:
First cached image removed first.

# ⌛ 4. TTL (Time To Live)

Each item expires after fixed time.
Useful when data changes regularly.

📌 Example:
Stock price cache valid for 30 seconds.

# ⚠️ Common Challenges

# 🧊 1. Cold Start

Cache is empty after restart, so first requests hit DB heavily.
Can cause temporary slowdown.

📌 Example:
Redis restarted → traffic suddenly hits MySQL.

# 🔄 2. Cache Invalidation

When source data changes, cache may become stale.
Keeping cache fresh is one of the hardest problems.

📌 Example:
Product price changed in DB but cache still shows old price.

# 🚨 3. Cache Stampede

Many users request same missing key at once and all hit DB together.
This can overload backend.

📌 Example:
Popular page cache expires during traffic spike.

# 🕳️ 4. Cache Penetration

Requests repeatedly ask for data that does not exist.
Cache misses keep hitting DB.

📌 Example:
Bots request invalid product IDs continuously.

# 🧠 Best Practices

Cache expensive and frequently requested data.
Use TTL to avoid stale data.
Use layered caching with browser + app cache + CDN.

📌 Example:
Images from CDN, sessions in Redis, analytics query results in app cache.

# 🚀 Real-World Example

Netflix caches popular movie metadata and thumbnails so users get fast browsing experience.
Without caching, every request would overload backend databases.

